  "texts": [
    "I. INTRODUCTIONEnsuring the dependability of software systems remains one of the most pressing challenges in the realm of computer science [1]- [3].",
    "As these systems grow in complexity and scale, traditional methodologies for identifying and mitigating potential faults increasingly struggle to keep pace [4], [5].Software fault injection has historically provided valuable means to ensure that the system will be safe even in the presence of residual software faults (or bugs) [6], [7].",
    "However, existing approaches to fault injection are often limited by the heavy reliance on predefined fault models, which may not adequately represent realistic failure scenarios encountered in real-world applications [8], [9].",
    "Furthermore, significant technical expertise and manual effort for configuration and execution are required for these approaches to be implemented successfully [10], [11].",
    "As a result, it is really difficult to achieve representativeness, and thus effectiveness, at an acceptable cost in real-world application scenarios."
  ],
